column15:
Action"":""1. ADFS key material can be accessed for legitimate purposes. Investigate this by using the following questions:
- Was this active directory object accessed legitimately? 
- Is the process that made the LDAP query related to known and recognized ADFS blatempistrative activity?
- Is the account that performed this action is expected to perform an ADFS blatempistrative activity?
- Does account owner recognize this activity?
- What is the role of the machine that the query was executed from? 
- Is the host part of an ADFS infrastructure and expected to be performing this action?

2. If the activity is identified as suspicious
column16: check if the key material was retrieved successfully.\nThe ACL applied to the key object in Active Directory typically means that it can only be successfully queried by a member of Domain Administrators
column20: or a member of the local blatempistrators group of the ADFS server. If this query was launched by an account that is a member of one of these groups
column21: it is likely that the key material was successfully accessed.\n\n3. Check for other suspicious activity executed on devices that belong to your ADFS network. Look for other suspicious activity executed by the account that performed the LDAP query and on the device it was executed from. Analyze the activity by the process which performed the lookup for other suspicious actions.""

Action"":""Validate the alert 
1. Check with the user of this machine to see if these commands were intentional.
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. If you determine this to be a true positive
column16: consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then
column17:
contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation 
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
3. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular
column18: ensure that you have installed the latest software
column20: and Operating System versions. \n4. If credential theft is suspected

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest

column4: followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp
column5: UNC2165
column6: and Indrik Spider.

•	Contact your incident response team.
NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team
column17: contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic investigation. A forensic investigation is important to identify Indicators of Compromise (IoC) that may be used to prevent other machines from installing the malware.\n•\tCheck if files on the affected machine were encrypted by ransomware.\n        o\tIf files were encrypted
column18:
disconnect the machine from the network as soon as possible.
•	Check for other suspicious events in the machine timeline.
•	Check for the observed deleted file name or SHA1 on other machines in the network.
•	Find the infection source and block it (IP or email)
•	Rebuild the affected machine.
•	After the affected machine has been rebuilt: 
         o	Ensure your software has the latest patch
column20: and close the vectors of attack.\n         o\tMove out-of-date applications to other systems to reduce the attack surface.\n         o\tConfigure your Trust Center to disable macros.""

column1: e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015❖2024-07-04 22:35:01.061459+00:00❖Manatee Tempest activity group❖Manatee Tempest activity group❖High❖"The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.
Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest
column2: an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download
column3: including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access
column4: followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp
column5: UNC2165
column6: and Indrik Spider.

column1: e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015❖2024-07-04 22:35:01.107822+00:00❖System recovery setting tampering❖System recovery setting tampering❖High❖"System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.
Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems
column2: such as a backup catalog
column3: volume shadow copies
column4: and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

column1: Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]

•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]"❖MDATP❖Microsoft❖3e6bd315-8c89-4a24-8579-9601035ef416_1❖62857e21-c95b-4124-457c-3bdcef05583f❖❖❖WindowsDefenderAtp❖❖❖False❖2024-06-20 09:32:00.329557+00:00❖2024-06-20 09:32:03.749465+00:00❖2024-07-04 22:34:59.885907+00:00❖"[""1. column1: e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015❖2024-07-04 22:35:01.515191+00:00❖System recovery setting tampering❖System recovery setting tampering❖High❖"System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.
Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems
column2: such as a backup catalog
column3: volume shadow copies
column4: and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

column1: Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]

•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]"❖MDATP❖Microsoft❖5984c937-d71d-4fb9-9eb9-e0eddb531b1c_1❖65e0e94f-36d8-f3a7-039e-c1770857c3ce❖❖❖WindowsDefenderAtp❖❖❖False❖2024-06-20 09:10:48.076628+00:00❖2024-06-20 09:10:50.905677+00:00❖2024-07-04 22:34:59.891911+00:00❖"[""1. column2: Windows Server 2016 and later versions
column3: iOS
column4: and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

column1: e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015❖2024-07-04 22:35:02.226256+00:00❖System recovery setting tampering❖System recovery setting tampering❖High❖"System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.
Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems
column2: such as a backup catalog
column3: volume shadow copies
column4: and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

column1: Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]

•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]"❖MDATP❖Microsoft❖7d47542a-7c5a-4fd4-85f2-640f2bf0927b_1❖37ed1840-2428-9ace-8db4-fc7ceeda30b9❖❖❖WindowsDefenderAtp❖❖❖False❖2024-06-20 09:10:49.054537+00:00❖2024-06-20 09:10:51.876113+00:00❖2024-07-04 22:34:59.902639+00:00❖"[""1. Action"":""A. Validate the alert.
1. Identify unusual system activity with system owners. Check if there is a legitimate reason for accessing the remote resource.
2. Check for similar activity on other devices within the same network to identify possible ongoing infection.

Action"":""There is no one-size-fits-all response if you have been targeted by ransomware. There is no guarantee that handing over the ransom will give you access to your files again. Paying the ransom could also make you a target for more malware.

•	Contact your incident response team.
NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team
column16: contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic investigation. A forensic investigation is important to identify Indicators of Compromise (IoC) that may be used to prevent other devices from installing the malware.\n•\tCheck if files on the affected device were encrypted by ransomware.\n        o\tIf files were encrypted
column17:
disconnect the device from the network as soon as possible.
•	Check for other suspicious events in the device timeline.
•	Find the infection source and block it (IP or email)
•	Rebuild the affected device.
•	After the affected device has been rebuilt: 
         o	Ensure your software has the latest patch
column19:
and close the vectors of attack.
         o	Move out-of-date applications to other systems to reduce the attack surface.
         o	Deploy the Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit (EMET) utility for behavioral-based exploit prevention.
         o	Configure your Trust Center to disable macros.""

column15:
Action"":""There is no one-size-fits-all response if you have been targeted by ransomware. There is no guarantee that handing over the ransom will give you access to your files again. Paying the ransom could also make you a target for more malware.

•	Contact your incident response team.
NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team
column16: contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic investigation. A forensic investigation is important to identify Indicators of Compromise (IoC) that may be used to prevent other devices from installing the malware.\n•\tCheck if files on the affected device were encrypted by ransomware.\n        o\tIf files were encrypted
column17:
disconnect the device from the network as soon as possible.
•	Check for other suspicious events in the device timeline.
•	Find the infection source and block it (IP or email)
•	Rebuild the affected device.
•	After the affected device has been rebuilt: 
         o	Ensure your software has the latest patch
column19:
and close the vectors of attack.
         o	Move out-of-date applications to other systems to reduce the attack surface.
         o	Deploy the Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit (EMET) utility for behavioral-based exploit prevention.
         o	Configure your Trust Center to disable macros.""

and determine scope

Initiate containment & mitigation

3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular
column22: ensure that you have installed the latest software
column24: and Operating System versions. \n5. If credential theft is suspected

Action"":""A. Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that is related to the alert. Inspect parent processes and the context of their execution.
2. Note the new user account that was added.
3. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
4. Check files for prevalence
column17:
and digital signatures.​
5. Check the device timeline for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert.
6. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident. 
1. Find related alerts and activities within the device. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph. 
2. Identify unexpected processes
column20: submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors. \n3. Identify communications to devices
column22:
and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach. 
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected
column23:
isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Decommission or reset passwords of the compromised or added accounts.
4. Block IP addresses and URLs. 
5. Install security updates.

D. Contact your incident response team or contact Microsoft support for investigation and remediation services.""

and determine scope

3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information.

column20: consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then
column21:
contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular
column22: ensure that you have installed the latest software
column24: and Operating System versions. \n5. If credential theft is suspected
column25: reset all relevant users passwords. \n6. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression. \n7. Block communication with relevant URLs or IPs at the organization’s perimeter.""

Query"":""// The query_now parameter represents the time (in UTC) at which the scheduled analytics rule ran to tbayuce this alert.
set query_now = datetime(2024-08-01T12:42:18.0385825Z);
SquidProxy
| where TimeGenerated > ago(1h)
| extend Domain = tostring(iif(Url startswith ""http""
column13:
':')[0]))
| project-rename ProxyUrl = Url
| join kind=inner (ThreatIntelligenceIndicator 
    | where isnotempty(Url) and TimeGenerated > ago(14d) and Active==true
    | extend Url_details = parse_url(Url)
    | where Url_details.Scheme == 'http' or (Url_details.Scheme == 'https' and Url_details.Path == '')
    | extend Url = iif(Url_details.Scheme == 'http'
column28:
Domain=Url)
    on $left.Domain == $right.Domain
| join kind=inner (DeviceNetworkInfo
    | where TimeGenerated > ago(2d)
    | mv-expand IPAddresses
    | extend IPAddress = parse_json(IPAddresses)
    | where IPAddress.IPAddress startswith ""10.60""
    | distinct DeviceName
